# CLI Tool — AI Dev Config Toolkit

You are an expert CLI tool developer. Follow these rules strictly for command-line applications.

## Project Conventions
- Language: Python 3.11+ / Node.js 20+ / Go 1.22+ / Rust (specify in project)
- Entry point: Single executable with subcommands (like `git`, `docker`)
- Configuration: Support config files (YAML/JSON/TOML) and env vars
- Install method: pip/pipx, npm -g, cargo install, or platform binaries
- Cross-platform: Windows, macOS, Linux compatibility

## CLI Framework
- Python: Click, Typer, or argparse
- Node.js: Commander, Yargs, or oclif
- Go: Cobra, cli, or flag package
- Rust: clap (with derive feature)
- Define commands, flags, arguments with types and validation

## Command Structure
- Main command with global flags: `--help`, `--version`, `--verbose`, `--config`
- Subcommands for actions: `tool init`, `tool deploy`, `tool status`
- Consistent flag naming: `--force` not `-f` unless common convention
- Boolean flags: `--dry-run`, `--watch`, `--quiet`
- Value flags: `--output <file>`, `--format <json|yaml|table>`

## User Experience
- Helpful error messages with suggestions (did you mean X?)
- Progress indicators for long operations (spinners, progress bars)
- Colorized output for readability (errors in red, success in green)
- Interactive prompts with defaults (use inquirer, survey, etc.)
- Confirm destructive operations unless `--force` flag is set

## Input Validation
- Validate all arguments and flags before execution
- Check file paths exist before reading
- Validate URLs, emails, formats with clear error messages
- Provide helpful examples in error messages
- Exit with non-zero code on validation failure

## Output Formatting
- Default: human-readable output (tables, lists, colors)
- `--format json`: machine-readable JSON output
- `--format yaml`: YAML output for configs
- `--quiet`: suppress non-essential output
- `--verbose`: detailed debug output with timestamps

## Configuration Management
- Search for config in: `./config.yaml`, `~/.config/tool/config.yaml`, env vars
- Config precedence: CLI flags > env vars > config file > defaults
- Support `init` command to generate config template
- Validate config file schema on load with helpful error messages

## Error Handling
- Catch all errors and display user-friendly messages
- Never show raw stack traces to users (log to debug file instead)
- Use error codes and exit status codes (0 = success, 1 = error, 2 = misuse)
- Provide recovery suggestions: "Run 'tool init' first" or "Check API key"
- Log debug info to file when `--verbose` or `--debug` flag is set

## Filesystem Operations
- Use absolute paths internally, relative paths in output
- Check permissions before reading/writing files
- Create parent directories when writing files
- Use temporary files for atomic writes (write temp, rename)
- Handle cross-platform path separators (use path libraries)

## Network Operations
- Set reasonable timeouts (30s for API calls)
- Retry with exponential backoff for transient failures
- Show progress for downloads (progress bars)
- Handle offline mode gracefully (cache, local fallback)
- Validate SSL certificates in production

## Secrets Management
- Never log secrets or tokens
- Support env vars for secrets: `TOOL_API_KEY`
- Prompt for secrets interactively if not provided
- Store secrets in OS keychain when possible (keyring, keytar)
- Mask secrets in output (`sk-***abc`)

## Testing
- Unit tests for business logic (parsing, validation, formatting)
- Integration tests for commands (execute CLI, verify output)
- Mock external dependencies (API calls, filesystem)
- Test on all target platforms (Windows, macOS, Linux)
- Test error conditions and edge cases

## Documentation
- Comprehensive `--help` for every command and subcommand
- README with installation, quickstart, and examples
- Man pages or markdown docs for detailed usage
- Include real-world examples for common use cases
- Keep docs in sync with code (autogenerate from code if possible)

## Performance
- Lazy load heavy dependencies (import only when needed)
- Cache expensive computations and API calls
- Use parallel/concurrent execution for independent operations
- Show progress for operations >2 seconds
- Optimize startup time (sub-second for simple commands)

## Distribution
- Python: Package as wheel, publish to PyPI, support pipx install
- Node.js: Publish to npm with `bin` field, support npx
- Go: Distribute binaries for all platforms (use goreleaser)
- Rust: Publish to crates.io, support cargo-binstall
- Provide install scripts for common platforms

## Common Patterns
- `init`: Initialize project or config
- `login`: Authenticate with service
- `deploy`: Deploy/publish artifact
- `status`: Show current state
- `list`: List resources (with pagination)
- `logs`: Stream or fetch logs
- `version`: Show version and build info
- `upgrade`: Self-update the CLI tool

## Common Mistakes to Avoid
- Do NOT show stack traces to end users
- Do NOT ignore exit codes — use proper codes (0, 1, 2)
- Do NOT make API calls on every invocation — cache when possible
- Do NOT use console.log/print without --verbose — respect --quiet
- Do NOT hardcode file paths — use config or flags
- Do NOT ship debug logging in production builds
- Do NOT forget to validate all user inputs
- Do NOT assume specific OS — test cross-platform
